    <section id="sect-00004">
    <title>Conjugate Addition of Alkyl Groups: Organocopper Reactions</title>
    <para id="para-00007">The conjugate addition of an alkyl or other organic group to an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated ketone (but not aldehyde) is one of the more useful 1,4-addition reactions, just as direct addition of a Grignard reagent is one of the more useful 1,2-additions.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00006">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein an alpha beta-unsaturated ketone reacts with a pink hydronium ion and blue R anion having a pair of electrons to form a product. The alpha beta-unsaturated ketone shows a carbonyl group with a pink oxygen the carbon of carbonyl group shows an open bond on the left; the carbon is bonded to another carbon on the right which has an open bond at the bottom and is double bonded to another carbon having two open bonds. The structure of product shows a carbonyl group with a pink oxygen the carbon of carbonyl group shows an open bond on the left and is bonded to another carbon on the right which is bonded to a pink hydrogen and shows an open bond at the bottom the carbon is bonded to another carbon having two open bonds at the top and a side bond with blue R.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_19_13_006.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00008">Conjugate addition of an organic group is carried out by treating the <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated ketone with a lithium diorganocopper reagent, R<sub>2</sub>CuLi. As we saw in <emphasis effect="bold"><link document="m00119">Section 10.7</link></emphasis>, lithium diorganocopper (Gilman) reagents are prepared by reaction between 1 equivalent of copper(I) iodide and 2 equivalents of an organolithium regent, RLi. The organolithium reagent, in turn, is formed by reaction of lithium metal with an organohalide in the same way that a Grignard reagent is prepared by reaction of magnesium metal with an organohalide.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00007">
    <media alt="A two part illustration shows two reactions of conjugate addition of an organic group. The first reaction shows RX (pink R) reacting with 2 moles of blue lithium and pentane to for RLi (pink R bonded to blue lithium) and Li cation bonded to X anion. The second reaction shows 2 moles of RLi (pink R) reacting with blue copper iodide and ether to form lithium diorganocopper (Gilman reagent) comprising of a lithium cation bonded to a complex having pink R bonded to blue copper anion bonded to pink R and another product having lithium cation bonded to iodine anion.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_19_13_007.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00009">Primary, secondary, and even tertiary alkyl groups undergo the conjugate addition reaction, as do aryl and alkenyl groups. Alkynyl groups, however, react poorly in the conjugate addition process. Diorganocopper reagents are unique in their ability to give conjugate addition products. Other organometallic reagents, such as Grignard reagents and organolithiums, normally result in direct carbonyl addition on reaction with <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated ketones.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00008">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two reactions for a common reactant. The first reaction shows 2-cyclohexenone (with pink oxygen) reacting with blue methyl magnesium bromide ether or blue CH3Li to form 1-Methyl-2-cyclohexen-1-ol (95%). 1-methyl-2-cyclohexen-1-ol shows a cyclohexene bonded to a pink hydroxyl group and blue methyl group at C2. The second reaction shows 2-cyclohexenone (with pink oxygen) reacting with blue Li(CH3)2Cu ether and pink hydronium ion to form 3-Methylcyclohexanone (97%). The structure of 3-Methylcyclohexanone shows cyclohexanone (pink oxygen) bonded to a blue methyl group at C3.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_19_13_008.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00010">The mechanism of this reaction is thought to involve conjugate nucleophilic addition of the diorganocopper anion, <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mtext>R</m:mtext><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mtext>Cu</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mo>–</m:mo></m:msup></m:mrow></m:math>, to the unsaturated ketone to give a copper-containing intermediate. Transfer of an R group from copper to carbon, followed by elimination of a neutral organocopper species, RCu, gives the final product.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00009">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein an unsaturated ketone reacts with a compound having a blue lithium cation bonded to R2Cu anion to form a copper containing intermediate which forms blue Rcu and an anion; the intermediate product further reacts with pink hydronium ion to form the final product. The unsaturated ketone shows a carbonyl group (pink oxygen) with an open bond on the left bonded to a second carbon that shows a free bond at the bottom and is double bonded to a third carbon having two open bonds. The first intermediate shows a carbon bonded to an open bond on the left the carbon is bonded to a pink oxygen anion at the top; the carbon is double bonded to a second carbon that shows an open bond at the bottom; the second carbon is bonded to a third carbon having two open bonds at the top; the third carbon is bonded to a blue copper bonded to two blue R; the second intermediate is similar to the first intermediate but C3 shows two free bonds and is bonded to blue R. The final product shows a carbonyl group (pink oxygen) with an open bond on the left bonded to a second carbon that shows a free bond and bonded to a pink hydrogen at the bottom. The second carbon is bonded to third carbon that shows two bonds at the top. The third carbon is bonded to a blue R on the right.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_19_13_009.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <example id="exam-00001">
    <title>Using a Conjugate Addition Reaction</title>
    <para id="para-00011">How might you use a conjugate addition reaction to prepare 2-methyl-3- propylcyclopentanone?</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00010">
    <media alt="An illustration shows the structure of 2-Methyl-3-propylcyclopentane. It shows a cyclopentane with C1 double bonded to an oxygen C2 bonded to a methyl group and C3 bonded to a propyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_19_13_010.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00012"><title>Strategy</title> A ketone with a substituent group in its <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis> position might be prepared by a conjugate addition of that group to an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>,<emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-unsaturated ketone. In the present instance, the target molecule has a propyl substituent on the <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis> carbon and might therefore be prepared from 2-methyl-2-cyclopentenone by reaction with lithium dipropylcopper.</para>
    <para id="para-00013"><title><span class="cyan-text">Solution</span></title></para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00011">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein 2-Methyl-2-cyclopentenone reacts with blue lithium dipropylcopper ether and hydronium ion and forms 2-Methyl-3-propylcylopentanone. 2-Methyl-2-cyclopentenone shows a cyclopentenone (pink oxygen) bonded to a methyl group at C2. 2-Methyl-3-propylcylopentanone shows cyclopentanone bonded to a methyl group at C2 and a blue propyl group at C3.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_19_13_011.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </example>
